..TEXT:
|m'andava io~: The so-called pleonastic reflexive,
together with the subject pronoun in this case, serves to set off the
subject Dante in his blind advance through smoke which is so painful to
the eyes and so filthy that he cannot open them to see.  |amaro~: See
Virgil, ^Aen.~ XII, 588: "fumoque implevit amaro" ("and filled it with
stinging smoke").
