..TEXT:
|calendi~: From the Latin ^calendae.~  See E. G.
Parodi (1957), p. 248.  In Dante's time the term was still used
of the first day of the month.  Cf. ^Calendimaggio~, "May Day."
Thus Dante is said to speak as the living do, dividing tirne into
months.  Benvenuto remarks that "mortui non dividunt tempus, quia
tempus non currit eis."  ("The dead know no division of time,
since time does not pass for them.")
